{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647373"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:43:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:43:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18244"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18244"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.14,0.67,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10958"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73927"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10958"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18244"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59402"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1253"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5825"},{"type":"tags","id":"7422"},{"type":"tags","id":"8490"},{"type":"tags","id":"10330"},{"type":"tags","id":"11420"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25464"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25465"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73927"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a complaint of pain in the lower buttock region, particularly when sitting for prolonged periods. She is a long-distance runner and has recently increased her training intensity. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is tenderness over a bony prominence in the lower buttock region, which is exacerbated by palpation and resisted knee flexion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following anatomical structures is most likely the source of her pain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sacrum","Greater trochanter","Ischial tuberosity","Iliac crest","Pubic symphysis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings are consistent with pain originating from the \u003Cstrong\u003Eischial tuberosity\u003C/strong\u003E. This bony prominence is located on the inferior part of the pelvis and serves as the attachment site for the hamstring muscles. It is commonly referred to as the \u0027sitting bone\u0027 because it bears weight when sitting. The increased training intensity in a long-distance runner can lead to overuse injuries in this area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater trochanter\u003C/strong\u003E is a bony prominence on the femur and is not typically associated with pain in the lower buttock region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eiliac crest\u003C/strong\u003E is the uppermost part of the pelvis and is not located in the lower buttock region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epubic symphysis\u003C/strong\u003E is located at the front of the pelvis and is not associated with buttock pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esacrum\u003C/strong\u003E is a triangular bone at the base of the spine and is not typically associated with pain in the lower buttock region.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The ischial tuberosity is a bony prominence located on the inferior part of the pelvis.","It serves as the attachment site for the hamstring muscles.","The ischial tuberosity is commonly referred to as the \u0027sitting bone\u0027 because it bears weight when sitting."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59402"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18244"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59402"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T08:03:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T08:05:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10958"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73927"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"